’ or ‘chamber-servant’, or a topographic name for someone who lived in a small cottage, or a habitational name from any of various minor places called from this word in Somerset, Sussex, Essex, and Peeblesshire. Compare   Bowerman   and   Bowring  .","English: variant of   Bowyer  , for a maker or seller of bows or an archer, from Middle English <i>bowyere</i>, an agent derivative of Old English <i>boga</i> ‘bow’.","Americanized form of German   Bauer   ‘peasant’ or ‘neighbor, fellow citizen’, or of its Dutch cognate   Bouwer  ."]},{"name":"Barrowman","meanings":["English and Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Bowerman  ."]},{"name":"Boorman","meanings":["English: variant of   Bowerman  ."]},{"name":"Boarman","meanings":["English: variant of   Bowerman  .","Perhaps also an altered form of German   Bormann  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Bowerman was born on 23 March 1383, in Chipping, Lancashire, England. She married William Braybrook in 1402, in Chipping, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died on 25 May 1428, in Chipping, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 45."},"et":{"23 March 1383–25 May 1428":"23. märts 1383–25. mai 1428","1383–1431":"1383–1431","1403–1447":"1403–1447","1383–1428":"1383–1428","1447":"1447","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1431":"1431","25 May 1428":"25. mai 1428","18 October 1403":"18. oktoober 1403","1383":"1383","23 March 1383":"23. märts 1383","1428":"1428","Chipping, Lancashire, England":"Chipping, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"23 March 1383–25 May 1428":"23. maaliskuuta 1383–25. toukokuuta 1428","1383–1431":"1383–1431","1403–1447":"1403–1447","1383–1428":"1383–1428","1447":"1447","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1431":"1431","25 May 1428":"25. toukokuuta 1428","18 October 1403":"18. lokakuuta 1403","1383":"1383","23 March 1383":"23. maaliskuuta 1383","1428":"1428","Chipping, Lancashire, England":"Chipping, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"23 March 1383–25 May 1428":"23 mars 1383–25 mai 1428","1383–1431":"1383–1431","1403–1447":"1403–1447","1383–1428":"1383–1428","1447":"1447","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1431":"1431","25 May 1428":"25 mai 1428","18 October 1403":"18 octobre 1403","1383":"1383","23 March 1383":"23 mars 1383","1428":"1428","Chipping, Lancashire, England":"Chipping, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Bowerman est née le 23 mars 1383, à Chipping, Lancashire, Angleterre. Elle a épousé William Braybrook en 1402, à Chipping, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Elle est décédée le 25 mai 1428, à Chipping, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 45 ans."},"de":{"23 March 1383–25 May 1428":"23. März 1383–25. Mai 1428","1383–1431":"